
[1]disavow

   DISAVOW, v.t. [dis and avow. See Vow.]

   1. To deny; to disown; to deny to be true, as a fact or charge
   respecting ones self; as, he was charged with embezzlement, but he
   disavows the fact. A man may disavow his name or signature; he may
   disavow a knowledge of a fact, or his concern in a transaction. Opposed
   to own or acknowledge.

   2. To deny; to disown; to reject.

   3. To dissent from; not to admit as true or justifiable; not to
   vindicate.

   The Envoy disavowed some parts of the Presidents proclamation.
